Troubleshooting Tips
Port Already in Use

# Find process using port
sudo lsof -i :8080
sudo lsof -i :8443

# Kill process if needed
sudo kill -9 <PID>
Caddy Won't Start

# Check Caddyfile syntax
caddy validate --config config/Caddyfile

# Check Caddy logs
journalctl -u caddy -n 50

# Manually test Caddy
caddy run --config config/Caddyfile
Encryption Errors

Verify both client and server use identical salt values
Ensure password matches on both sides
Check cryptography library version: pip3 show cryptography
Verify PBKDF2 parameters match (iterations, algorithm, key length)
Connection Refused

Verify listener is running: ps aux | grep encrypted_listener
Check firewall rules: sudo ufw status
Ensure correct host/port in client configuration
Test direct connection: telnet localhost 8080
SSL Certificate Errors

Use -k flag with curl for self-signed certificates
Verify Caddy generated internal certificates
Check certificate location: ~/.local/share/caddy/certificates/
Conclusion
This lab demonstrated deploying an encrypted C2 listener with HTTPS tunneling using Caddy as a reverse proxy. You implemented encryption using Python's cryptography library, created automated management scripts, and validated secure communications. This architecture provides a foundation for understanding how modern C2 frameworks hide malicious traffic within legitimate HTTPS connections.

Key takeaways:

HTTPS tunneling obscures C2 traffic as normal web traffic
Encryption adds defense-in-depth for C2 communications
Automation scripts simplify deployment and management
Proper validation prevents configuration errors
Understanding both client and server components is essential
In production red team operations, additional considerations include domain fronting, certificate pinning, traffic shaping, and jitter to evade detection.
